---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const chapters = [
  ['01', 'Origin', '#honolulu-to-everett'],
  ['02', 'Map', '#the-map-on-the-porch'],
  ['03', 'Comeback', '#valedictorian-trinity-dropout-comeback'],
  ['04', 'Capital', '#two-billionaire-family-offices'],
  ['05', 'Film', '#a-brief-entertainment-career'],
  ['06', 'Pivot', '#the-pivot'],
  ['07', 'Thesis', '#why-this-combination-matters'],
];
---

<Base
  title="About — Alex Schulz"
  description="The long version: Honolulu to Everett, Paul Allen’s family office to David Lynch productions, summa cum laude accounting to a USGIF-accredited geospatial master’s."
>
  <section class="relative border-b border-hairline bg-paper-soft/45">
    <div class="section-shell pt-16 pb-12 md:pt-24 md:pb-16">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="coord mb-8 text-accent">About</p>
        <h1 class="section-heading mb-6 text-5xl md:text-6xl">
          The long version.
        </h1>
        <p class="text-xl leading-snug text-ink-soft md:text-2xl">
          A CPA with a master's in geospatial intelligence. There are an estimated 10-20 people in the
          United States with that combination. This is how one of them got here.
        </p>
      </div>

      <dl class="mt-10 grid max-w-3xl grid-cols-1 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="surface-quiet rounded-md p-4">
          <dt class="coord text-accent">Base</dt>
          <dd class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold">Lake Stevens</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-quiet rounded-md p-4">
          <dt class="coord text-signal">Training</dt>
          <dd class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold">CPA / GEOINT</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-quiet rounded-md p-4">
          <dt class="coord">Thread</dt>
          <dd class="mt-2 text-lg font-semibold">Spatial finance</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>

      <div class="mt-8 grid max-w-5xl gap-4 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1fr)_23rem]">
        <div class="surface rounded-md p-5">
          <p class="coord text-accent">Working habit</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-soft">
            I get pulled toward the useful detail sitting just outside the frame: the map margin,
            the rail spur, the filing footnote, the small operational clue that changes the larger
            story.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="surface overflow-hidden rounded-md p-3">
          <div class="px-2 pb-3">
            <p class="coord text-signal">Soundtrack</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm font-semibold text-ink">Jadakiss - Things I've Been Through</p>
          </div>
          <iframe
            class="block h-[152px] w-full rounded-md border-0"
            title="Spotify Embed: Jadakiss - Things I've Been Through"
            src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/track/1nzOHmHda8NbuwGJjFz5fP?utm_source=generator&theme=0"
            allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture"
            loading="lazy"
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Article body, rendered with typography plugin -->
  <section class="relative">
    <div class="section-shell py-14 md:py-20">
      <nav
        class="mb-12 grid max-w-5xl grid-cols-2 border-y border-hairline bg-paper-soft/40 sm:grid-cols-4 lg:grid-cols-7"
        aria-label="About page chapters"
      >
        {chapters.map(([number, label, href]) => (
          <a
            href={href}
            class="group border-b border-r border-hairline px-3 py-4 transition-colors hover:bg-accent-soft sm:px-4 lg:border-b-0"
          >
            <span class="coord text-accent">{number}</span>
            <span class="mt-2 block text-sm font-semibold text-ink-soft transition-colors group-hover:text-accent">
              {label}
            </span>
          </a>
        ))}
      </nav>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-3xl prose-headings:font-sans prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-normal prose-headings:text-ink prose-p:text-ink-soft prose-p:leading-relaxed prose-strong:text-ink prose-strong:font-medium prose-a:text-accent prose-a:underline prose-a:decoration-hairline hover:prose-a:decoration-accent">
        <h2 id="honolulu-to-everett">Honolulu to Everett.</h2>
        <p>
          Born at Kapiolani Women &amp; Children's Hospital in Honolulu — the same hospital as Obama, for whatever that's worth.
          My mom lived in Hawaii for ten years; my dad for five. A year after I was born we moved to
          <strong>Everett, Washington</strong>, where my mom was from. Dad went east. I was an only child,
          raised by my mom — a dental assistant — and I was, by all accounts, a serious kid.
          When I was born the doctor told my mom I'd have wrinkles on my forehead by age five.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some childhood summers I was back in Hawaii, staying with my uncle <strong>Steve Ozark</strong>.
          Steve ran backstage catering in Hawaii for more than thirty years — across his career he
          cooked for Santana, Bob Dylan, Neil Diamond, Elton John, Jimmy Buffett, and many others. He
          was also a crew member on <em>The Glen Campbell Goodtime Hour</em> from 1969 to 1972. Through
          Steve I was backstage for Lil Wayne twice, Elton John, Kevin Hart, Shaquille O'Neal's All
          Star Comedy Jam, Steve Miller Band, and Boyz II Men. The summer after senior year I also
          helped him with a 70s soul revue: the Stylistics, the Chi-Lites, the Manhattans, the Main
          Ingredient. The lesson I took from Steve, even before I could articulate it, was that the
          world is smaller and more reachable than it looks. He knew everyone on Oahu. He passed away
          in 2014.
        </p>

        <h2 id="the-map-on-the-porch">The map on the porch.</h2>
        <figure class="not-prose my-10 overflow-hidden rounded-md border border-hairline bg-paper-soft">
          <img
            src="/images/industrial-map-of-washington.jpeg"
            alt="Framed Industrial Map of Washington from the family collection"
            class="block w-full"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption class="border-t border-hairline px-4 py-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-muted">
            Industrial Map of Washington, from my mom's grandparents' dairy farm in Custer,
            Washington.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>
          One of the objects that made maps feel personal was an old Industrial Map of Washington
          from my mom's grandparents' dairy farm in Custer, Washington. It had been hanging on the
          porch by a thumb tack until my mom took it home and framed it.
        </p>
        <p>
          I think that is part of why my work keeps circling back to maps: they show industry,
          movement, land, and memory at once. They are how hidden systems become visible.
        </p>
        <p>
          Land records became personal in another way, too. I helped my mom fight two adverse
          possession lawsuits with different neighbors: one settled, one won. It was an unwanted
          education in boundaries, documentation, recorded facts, and the gap between being right and
          being able to prove it.
        </p>

        <h2 id="valedictorian-trinity-dropout-comeback">Valedictorian, Trinity, dropout, comeback.</h2>
        <p>
          Graduated high school as <strong>valedictorian of Everett High School</strong>. It started as
          a family bet — Steve mailed me a hundred-dollar bill for every semester I got a 4.0, and by
          sophomore year I realized I might be able to keep it going. I went to
          <strong>Trinity University</strong> in San Antonio — ranked #40 among national liberal arts
          colleges, #1 in Texas — and didn't finish. I dropped out.
        </p>
        <p>
          After freshman year at Trinity, one of those strange doors opened: a job with
          <strong>Craig McCaw's family office</strong>. McCaw is a cellular-industry pioneer; I was
          flown down to Montecito, California, to help with properties there, including a property
          Craig had acquired from John Cleese. That fall, Trinity's annual speaker happened to be John
          Cleese, and I found myself in a private meet-and-greet telling him I had just worked at his
          former property.
        </p>
        <p>
          Came home, enrolled at <strong>Washington State University</strong>, and graduated
          <strong>summa cum laude</strong> with a BA in Accounting. Picked up the
          <strong>Delta Sigma Pi Scholarship Key</strong> — an award established in 1912 that goes to
          the student with the highest cumulative GPA across all of business and economics, regardless
          of fraternity membership. The dropout and the comeback happened in the same five years.
          I've earned a 4.0 in every program I've completed since.
        </p>
        <p>
          The geospatial thread was already trying to surface there. I wanted to minor in
          <strong>Geospatial Analysis</strong> at WSU, but the labs overlapped with the core accounting
          courses. I also became one of thirteen students selected for <strong>Cougs on Wall Street</strong>,
          a trip to New York City for the Quinnipiac GAME Forum funded by Gary Brinson. I volunteered
          with the Speakers Committee, too, which is how I got to meet Big Black from
          <em>Rob &amp; Big</em>, one of my favorite shows.
        </p>

        <h2 id="two-billionaire-family-offices">Two billionaire family offices.</h2>
        <p>
          The McCaw chapter happened unusually early; Vulcan came later, after the WSU comeback. At
          <strong>Vulcan Inc.</strong> — Paul Allen's family office — I worked as a staff accountant
          in Real Estate Finance in Seattle, managing monthly loan draws and portfolio variance
          analysis across eight real-estate projects. Vulcan also gave me an early personal-finance
          education: the 401(k) match was 50% up to the IRS contribution limit, so I was maxing it
          out in my 20s and learning what compounding actually does. Paul Allen co-founded Microsoft; at his passing
          his net worth was estimated at $20 billion. Between McCaw and Vulcan, I had a close-up view
          of how real money does accounting.
        </p>
        <p>
          Between and around them were the ordinary-sounding stops that do the bulk of actual craft
          development: fund administration at <strong>ALPS</strong>, real-estate development accounting
          at <strong>Pillar Properties</strong> (sole accountant on 15+ multimillion-dollar
          development projects), and aerospace accounting at <strong>Spaceflight Inc. / Firefly
          Aerospace</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>North Kai Capital</strong> was my first attempt to turn market curiosity into a
          product. After reading the Value Investing Congress winning thesis on Jack in the Box, I
          built an equity-index concept around publicly traded franchise companies. I worked with
          EQM Indexes in San Diego to refine the methodology and eligibility criteria, then launched
          it as a licensable index. EQM was later acquired, but the index methodology still exists as
          part of that earlier work.
        </p>

        <h2 id="a-brief-entertainment-career">A brief entertainment career.</h2>
        <p>
          There are two IMDB credits in my name — <strong>nm5681118</strong>. The first is
          <em>7 Minutes</em> (2014), a crime-thriller directed by Jay Martin. The second is
          <strong><em>Twin Peaks: The Return</em></strong> — David Lynch's 2017 revival — where I was
          an Accounting Clerk on the Washington state production team across ten episodes.
        </p>
        <p>
          Separate from those IMDb credits, during one of the Hawaii stays with Steve I worked on the
          season 20 finale of <em>The Amazing Race</em> as a production assistant and driver for host
          Phil Keoghan. I also worked the 2011 APEC meeting for Showcall USA, setting up umbrellas
          for Secret Service perimeter positions.
        </p>
        <p>
          None of it was strategic. I'd grown up adjacent to the industry through Steve and things
          happened to line up. It did teach me that production accounting is its own discipline — the
          logic is familiar but the pace and stakes are unlike anything in corporate finance.
        </p>
        <p>
          My twenties had a strange momentum to them. I kept finding myself in rooms I would not have
          known how to ask for: backstage in Hawaii, a Wall Street forum, billionaire family offices,
          film and television production. My thirties were different. The doors did not open as
          easily, the legal fights started, and life got heavier. That chapter gave me a different
          kind of education: endurance, documentation, and the need to build a direction instead of
          waiting for one.
        </p>

        <h2 id="the-pivot">The pivot.</h2>
        <p>
          During the pandemic I started the <strong>Graduate Certificate in Digital Mapping at the
          University of Kentucky</strong> — remote, through their New Maps Plus program. 4.0 GPA, and
          first contact with HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Git, and the whole modern geospatial stack: QGIS,
          Leaflet, Mapbox. It reframed accounting for me: every ledger is a dataset, and every
          dataset has a shape. I did it at night while working full-time in real-estate development
          accounting.
        </p>
        <p>
          A year later I was finishing a <strong>Master's in Geospatial Intelligence at the
          University of Maryland</strong> — also remote, also 4.0, also on nights and weekends. The
          program is USGIF-accredited — one of only 23 such programs in the country. My capstone was
          an interactive GIS map of rail-served real estate. That capstone became
          <strong>rail_served</strong>, and it's the thread I've been pulling on ever since. I flew
          to Denver for the GEOINT Symposium the year I graduated and met the team at BlackSky — the
          satellite company Paul Allen's Vulcan had backed years earlier. Some circles close quickly.
        </p>

        <h2 id="why-this-combination-matters">Why this combination matters.</h2>
        <p>
          There are roughly <strong>650,000 active CPAs</strong> in the United States. There are maybe
          <strong>20,000–35,000 living holders of a geospatial master's</strong> of any kind, and
          probably <strong>2,000–5,000 with a GEOINT master's specifically</strong>. The overlap —
          people who hold both a CPA license and a graduate geospatial credential — is an estimated
          <strong>10–20 people nationwide</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          These two fields don't share a career pipeline. CPAs come from accounting programs and go
          into public accounting or corporate finance. GEOINT graduates come from geography,
          environmental science, or intelligence and defense. The paths almost never cross.
        </p>
        <p>
          Meanwhile the financial world is racing in this direction. Oxford's Smith School, the Alan
          Turing Institute, and the Satellite Applications Catapult have formally founded the
          <strong>Spatial Finance Initiative</strong>. A Berkeley Haas study found that
          satellite-data-driven trades generated 4–5% returns within three days of earnings
          announcements. Nearly 70% of top hedge funds now use geospatial or satellite alternative
          data. The talent pipeline for "spatial finance" is, charitably, sparse.
        </p>

        <h2>What I'm building now.</h2>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/#project-item2">Item2</a></strong> is my own bet on that thesis — a
          geospatial intelligence platform that surfaces operational signals from satellite imagery
          and physical-world data around micro- and small-cap public companies. You can see a live
          version at <a href="https://item2.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">item2.io</a>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/#project-hodego">Hodego</a></strong> is a startup I co-founded — a
          platform connecting athletes with world-class coaches for personalized training and
          in-competition advice. Oversaw a team of three developers for eighteen months, made the
          architectural calls, shipped an MVP on AWS.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong><a href="/#project-rail-served">rail_served</a></strong> continues to evolve — the
          UMD capstone has expanded to cover Western US rail-served industrial property, and a
          TypeScript rebuild is underway.
        </p>
        <p>
          I am currently a senior accountant. The side projects are the thesis. If any of this lands
          for you, <a href="mailto:alex.j.schulz@gmail.com">write</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-14 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href="/resume.pdf"
          class="button-primary"
        >
          Resume <span class="mono text-xs">↓</span>
        </a>
        <a
          href="mailto:alex.j.schulz@gmail.com"
          class="button-secondary"
        >
          alex.j.schulz@gmail.com
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
